column58: Bolts or Nuts; Manway or Dome Cover
column168: On September 3rd, 2014 at 11:28 hours, FRA Rail Safety Hazardous Material Inspectors at the CSXT Frontier Yard discovered ACFX 71284, a loaded UN 1267, Petroleum Crude Oil tank car to have wetness coming from around the manway area, the FRA identified two less than tool tight manway swing bolts. The car was isolated and the Shipper, Bridger Trading, LLC, was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2014-09-03-00161. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, EP+S of Vermont the Buffalo Branch office was dispatched to the scene, upon inspection it was determined that manway cover swing bolts #6+7 were less than tool tight, this causing a release between the manway cover and the nozzle, during the securement of the manway swing bolts, a broken support ear was found on the #3 swing bolt which supports the retainer pin for proper closure of the manway cover.  Mr. Paul Ferguson, Rail Logistics Manager,was notified of the situation found. ACFX 71284 will be a transload, then cleaned + purged for Home Shop disposition.    This incident did require a special move.    Cause Code: 200 (5 points)  NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0)  = 100
column169: Discussed proper inspection of manway swing bolts, nozzle retainer pins and packing of a tank car with Mr. Ferguson.

column168: At 0415 ET hours, Mike Hart of R&L Carriers contacted ERTS regarding the release of approximately 1/2 pound of a UN3378 SODIUM CARBONATE PEROXYHYDRATE from a 50 (fifty) pound plastic bag to the rear of trailer at the Elllenwood, GA terminal. At the time of this report, no drains, soils or waterways were reported as being impacted. At this time, no regulatory reporting is required. Facility personnel stated this freight was received in damaged from the DCA terminal. Facility personnel stated they noticed the released product when they proceeded to unload the trailer. facility personnel stated that it appeared the impacted bag was struck by other freight resulting in the release. ERTS has dispatched a network contractor with an approximate ETA of 60 minutes to site. ERTS has requested copies of the BOL and MSDS. A copy of the spill incident report will be added to this alert when made available. The shipper is OCI Chemicals.The contractor is on site and reports they have found 3 (three) bags (so far) on 2 (two) separate pallets that have been damaged resulting in the release. The contractor over packed 3 torn bags and recovered product into 1-55 gallon drum. The drum was labelled and left on site to continue in transit. No wastes were generated.

A contractor was dispatched to the site and transferred the tote into a new tote to be sent onto the consignee. The damaged tote and cleanup debris were containerized for pending disposal.

column168: Tank car UTLX 677683 in the railyard was reported with a fresh commodity stain on its side shell that emanated from its top manway closure. No ground impact from this spillage was observed. UTLX 677683 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. On 9/04/2014, contract responders inspecting UTLX 677683 reported finding 7 of 8 manway securement eyebolts less than tool tight.  The manway gasket installed in the manway cover's gasket groove was inspected and deemed serviceable. The manway cover was closed and all manway securement eyebolts were properly tool tightened. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure.  The commodity spillage on the side shell and safety appliances were cleaned. Response was concluded by 1430 hrs. MDT, 9/04/2014. Intact shipper seals Suncor Energy 331485 and 331489 at the manway closure and protective housing cover respectively were replaced with seals TIS 5213 and 5204 respectively.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Driver was attempting to make left turn onto narrow road way. Left rear trailer wheels dropped into a ditch causing the trailer to over turn onto its left side.  Pressure relief valve developed a small leak but resealed itself.  A bucket was placed under the relief valve in case a leak redeveloped during transfer.  There was no package failure on this cargo tank.  Cargo tank was cosmetically damaged. This cargo tank will undergo complete cargo tank testing prior to being placed back into service.
column169: As a result of this incident, the company has implemented a policy for all drivers finding themselves in an unsafe manuvering situation to stop, activate four way flashers, and get out and look at the scene.  If they determine they cannot complete the manuver safely, they are instructed to contact central dispatch and obtain on site assistance prior to movement.

At 0315 ET hours, Randy Clark of R&L carriers contacted ERTs regarding the release of approximately 65 (sixty-five) gallons of a UN1814 POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE) from a 250 gallon tote to the concrete dock area and asphalt parking area at the East St Louis terminal. At the time of this report, no drains, soils or waterways were reported as being impacted. The RQ for POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE is 1000 pounds. At this time, no regulatory reporting is required. Facility personnel reported the tote was punctured by the mast on a fork lift resulting in the release. Facility personnel have applied soda ash to some of the impacted areas and have also built a dam around a nearby storm drain ( approximately 50 ft away) ERTS has requested copies of the BOL and MSDS. The shipper is Eaton Corp. ERTS has dispatched a network contractor with an approximate ETA of 60-90 minutes ETA to site. The contractor reports that they have transferred the remaining product into a replacement tote and estimates approximately 25 gallons was released. The contractor has applied absorbents and a neutralizer to the concrete dock area. The contractor will commence with neutralizing the trailer floor.

column168: After arrival of intermodal trailer GMLZ 536804 on an inbound BNSF train, GMLZ 536804 was observed leaking an unknown liquid substance during the deramp process from its intermodal flatcar. GMLZ 536804 was carefully moved and isolated at the facility's containment area for further investigation.  On 9/08/2014, contract responders inspecting the lading within GMLZ 536804 reported finding one 55 gallon steel drum with a dent and small crack at its bottom chime which allowed some contents inside this drum to escape. Responders placed this damaged drum inside an 85 gallon over-pack drum properly labeled and returned this over-pack drum to GMLZ 536804's lading after non-evaporated spillage inside GMLZ 536804 was absorbed and cleaned. The mixed lading within GMLZ 536804 was insufficiently blocked and braced which allowed drum movement that most likely caused this compromising drum damage.

column168: Tank car BNSF 880294, during an inbound mechanical inspection in the railyard, was reported leaking commodity from its bottom outlet. Containment was placed under BNSF 880294 to capture leaking liquid. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspecting BNSF 880294 reported the top operated bottom outlet valve's (TOBOV) operating rod was approximately four turns loose from its full closed position. Responders closed the TOBOV and the leak at the bottom outlet slowed but continued. The bottom outlet's closure cap (BOC) was tight. BNSF 880294 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard with portable containment in place under its bottom outlet.  On 9/02/2014 the commodity within BNSF 880294 was transferred into another suitable tank car without further incident and afterwards the commodity drips from the BOC ceased. The BOC was removed and inspected. The BOC gasket was found deteriorated/warped which allowed commodity to escape at this non-sealing BOC and from the non-closing TOBOV. The gasket was replaced and the BOC was properly tool tightened. Impacted ballast/soils were excavated and transported to a disposal facility. The excavation sites were backfilled with clean soil and ballast. Captured commodity was taken to a recycling facility. BNSF 880294 was directed to a qualified repair facility to determine and rectify the TOBOV's failure to fully close.

column168: At 2305 ET hours, Mike Hart of R&L Carriers contacted ERTS regarding the release of approximately 1/2 gallons of battery acid UN2794 BATTERIES WET with ACID, from a 1645 pound battery to the concrete floor of the dock area at the Ellenwood, GA terminal. At the time of this report, no drains, soils or waterways were reported as being impacted. At this time, no regulatory reporting is required. Facility personnel stated the weight of the battery caused a poorly constructed wooden pallet to break, causing the battery to fall over and resulting in the acid release. ERTS has dispatched a network contractor with an approximate ETA of 90 minutes.The contractor stated that a 1645 pound battery did release approximately 1/2 gallon of sulfuric acid the the concrete dock floor. The contractor stated the weight of the battery and poor condition of the wood pallet are the apparent cause. The contractor will apply a calcium based absorbent to the impacted areas and wipe down the battery casing.  The battery was placed on a stable, well made wooden pallet provided by the terminal and re-banded.

At the time of this report, no drains, soils or waterways were reported as being impacted. The RQ for SODIUM NITRITE is 100 pounds. At this time, no regulatory reporting is required. Facility personnel stated that it appeared the bag was torn when a skid of other freight collided causing the release. ERTS has dispatched a network contractor with an approximate ETA to site of 90 minutes. 5 bags in all were found to be damaged. The release was approximately 20 lbs combined. A calcium absorbent powder was placed in the drum with the overpacked bags. All 5 bags were put in 1 drum.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste arrived at the intended waste disposal facility. The lids were tightened and the spilled material was cleaned up with a suitable absorbent material which was placed in one of the drums.  The load was then unloaded at the intended waste disposal facility.  The spill was reported to the LA State police incident number 14-04057
column169: The origin location was notified to check tightness of all drums prior to loading.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste arrived at the intended waste disposal facility.  Upon doing his routine post trip inspection, the driver noticed a leaking drum.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and overpacked the drum into a suitable salvage container, along with the absorbent material used to clean up the spill from the trailer floor.  The load was then accepted into the ten day storage yard of the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The drum was not leaking at the time of pickup, nor during the entire trip to the disposal facility.  Apparently the rigors of transportation caused the corroded weld at the bottom of the old used drum to leak near the end of the journey.  The origin location was notified to inspect drums carefully prior to loading.

column168: A waste solvent tanker was loaded at the South Tank Farm (STF) at Pfizer Inc. in Kalamazoo, Mi at 9:35am September 15th 2014 and was observed leaking in transit. The tanker had 3 domes on the top where different connections could be made. The front dome was used to connect the TOx vent line and the middle and rear domes were not used. The middle and rear dome connections were not inspected prior to the tanker leaving. The vent line inside the rear dome was loose  and material began leaking during transitfrom that vent line. The tanker was observed  leaking by Valley City contractors and they stopped the tanker at the corner of Romence Rd and Portage Rd. This is a very short distance (1/4 mile) from where it left the Pfizer site. The splill occurred from the Pfizer  site to this location. Material that was spilled in that distance was cleaned up by Valley City Environmental Services, the 1 rear vent line where the leak occurred was tightened and the tanker was returned to the Pfizer site for inspection before being released for shipment.
column169: The following corrective actions are being taken to prevent any future re occurence.    1. The loading and inspection procedure will be updated to incorporate additional inspection requirements to include all vent lines.  2. The operators will be trained on the updated procedure.

column168: Tank car GATX 94664 in the railyard was reported leaking commodity on its side shell that emanated from its valve housing area. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material  responders inspecting GATX 94664 reported finding all four of the liquid valve's mounting pipe flange bolt nuts loose from 1 1/2 to 2 full turns. These loose nuts were tool tightened. Afterwards, the responder observed that a small leak continued from the mounting flange connection/gasket location.  GATX 94664 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard for furtherance. Later on 9/04/2014, contract responders replaced all of the old deteriorated gaskets (reported as stainless steel/flexible graphite gaskets) at the liquid valve's mounting connection and the liquid eduction tube connection with Viton gaskets. The liquid line valve was re-installed and properly secured. A nitrogen blanket was introduced into GATX 94664 to test for leakage and no pressure loss was gauged and no leaks detected. Non-evaporated spillage was cleaned.  OTMA FRA-14090630 was granted to transport GATX 94664 to the consignee for unloading and then to a qualified repair facility.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated  as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

Our driver was making a delivery on a construction site located at Road 123 Intersection with Road #9 in Ponce, Puerto Rico. While he was moving from one area of the site to another he forgot to disengage the PTO, resulting in an excess of pressure provoked by the continuous pumping of diesel. Given the excess presure that the hoses were subject to, the hose that connects the pump with the delivery system failed. Resulting in a spill of about 90 gallons of diesel on the 123 Road.  This spill also afected the entrance to the Cemex cement plant located nearby. The pump spilled liquid for about 20 seconds. Inmediately when the driver realized the situation he stopped the flow of the pump and made sure there was no more leakage. He proceeded to put absorbent pads in the area of the spill. We called 911 to get police and fire rescue personnel to the area. Then we called our environmental cleanup company to proceed with the first response. Our mechanics also where inmediately dispatched to the area.  We sent a different truck as a precaution to unload the hole amount contained in the truck involved in the spill. FMCSA inspectors arrived to the scene. They supervised the cleanup procedures and the unloading of the tank. Around 3pm the cleanup was finished.
column169: We suspended the driver for two weeks for the safety incident.  As an SOP or standard operating procedure exists all employees will be reminded of the importance of making things right.  We are contemplating feasible ways to make the truck unmovable when the PTO is engaged. Training will be conducted ASAP in regards to this incident as a learning experience for all our drivers and personnel.

column168: Material Handler was in the process of using a forklift to load a drum of new acetone product, as he proceded forward, his tines punctured the 55-gallon drum.  He immediately plugged the hole with absorbent wipes and placed the drum on its side or order to stop the leak.  He surrounded the drum with absorbent material and was successul in containing the spill. With the help of a second Material Handler, the drum was overpacked into an 85-gallon drum and the spill was cleaned entirely.  All clean up debris was drummed and prepared for shipment to the designated facility.
column169: A Management Team Investigation was completed and the result of this spill was determined to be human error. And though our Forklift Operator does hold a current and compliant certificate, we have required retraining using the following modules; Forklift Operatpr Training and Forklift Hands-on Evaluation.  In addition, a written warning was issued to the Material Handler.  We have designated all product preparing to be loaded to be placed in a designated area and having better lighting and visibility.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation, a 5-gallon pail fell off the pallet spilling approximately 2 gallons of material onto the containment floor of the van trailer. Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised  container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and  placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: A Management Team investigated the causes of the spill and determined the root cause as improper packaging.  Our recieiving team has been instructed to inspect and verify all materials received are in the proper UN-rated containers and there are no structure damage to the containers.  Additionally ensure all containers placed on pallets are secure before moving.

column168: A U.S. Xpress tractor trailer carrying a load full of UN2794, Batteries, Wet filled with acid, experienced a load shift which resulted in multiple batteries toppling over. Approximately 20 gallons of battery acid released onto the trailer floor after the batteries tipped over. A network contractor, United Professional Services (UPS), responded out of San Antonio, TX to neutralize the acid and re-stack the pallets. An on-site TX Environmental Health and Safety representative instructed UPS to re-stack all batteries that leaked acid onto a pallet labeled "damaged batteries." The trailer floor was re-cleaned and the shipment was re-loaded into a new clean trailer. All waste was non-hazardous once neutralized and taken with the contractor for proper disposal. The site was restored to its previous condition.

column168: At 2010 ET hours, Rosa BEhn with R&L Carriers contatced ERTS regarding the release of approximately 27 (twenty-seven) gallons of a UN1760 CORROSIVE LIQUID NOS - POLY PHOSPHORIC ACID SOLUTION to the rear of a trailer, concrete dock area and asphalt parking lot at the Ellenwood GA terminal. At the time of this report, no drains, soils or waterways were reported as being impacted. At this time, no regulatory reporting is required. The Federal RQ for Phosphoric Acid is 5000 ponds. The caller stated that an apparent load shift in transit has resulted in the release. The caller stated that other OTR drivers noticed a liquid leaking from the rear of the trailer in transit and advised the driver to pull over. The driver drove to the terminal with out making any stop. ERTS has dispatched a network contractor with an approximate ETA of 90 minutes to the scene. ERTS has requested copies of the BOL and MSDS. The shipper is J Tech Sales.The contractor reports arriving on site and finding a steel drum on its side from an apparent load shift in transit. The product released from the cap bung and released the product to the entire floor of the trailer impacted the bottom of the wooden pallets. The contractor estimates approximately 25-30 gallons.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: Twelve (12) large Lead-Acid batteries were placed on two pallets to ship for recycling. The batteries were secured to the pallets with shrink-wrap. The batteries were however, very old and the plastic was brittle.    When the shipment arrived at the Veolia facility in Flanders, NJ it was discovered that due to the normal vibrations and movement of the vehicle while in transportation, one of the weakened batteries cracked and began leaking acid. The leaked material was neurtalized and remediated. All batteries were over-packed in drums prior to continuing transportation.
column169: Training will be completed for all employees regarding the spill concerns related to shipping old, brittle batteries.  These batteries are to be packaged in drums prior to transportation.

column168: A R&L box truck was carrying a shipment of corrosive liquids. (1) 5-gallon pail experienced the release of approximately 5 gallons of UN3266 Sodium Nitrite onto the truck floor and asphalt below at Randall Children's Hospital in Portland, OR on September 17, 2014. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted. The dispatched contractor, Belfor environmental, conducted clean-up and remediation activities the same day. The released alkaline was stabilized and containerized for disposal. The impacted area of asphalt was also cleaned. All contaminated materials and damaged pail was taken with Belfor for final disposal. The site was restored to its previous condition.

column168: The tractor trailer that was proceeding on route 128 South and continued straight across the lanes striking the median guardrail, it rode along the guardrail before laying over the guardrail and coming to a stop. It was reported immediately upon arrival of the emergency responders that the driver was deceased. A load of liquid asphalt at 320° F leaked out of a hole in the front head that was caused when the tanker struck the median guardrail. The body couldn't be extricated until the unit was up righted. In order to upright the vehicle it had to be offloaded. The release lasted for approximately 7 hours before the tanker was emptied. The release continued approximately 465 feet within a swale before cooling down enough to coagulate. Drains were protected by the emergency responders with sand.
column169: To date, through the investigation, it was ground that from the time of the lane departure that there was no evidence of any response from the driver. It is believed that there was a medical issue. Where there was no other party involved, the State police did not request an autopsy.

column168: The drum arrived at the terminal and whe the trailer door was opened a pungent odor was smelled. The cap form the drum has some residula around it.

While the Veolia employee was exiting his truck at the 10 day intransit facility parking lot he walked to the rear of the truck and notice a drop of liquid on the ground and another drop on the side of the truck. The Veolia employee quickly notified the Veolia faciity staff, who than assisted him in locating the source of the leak. The leaking drum was identified, placed on its side and further overpacked into a 85 gallon drum. The small amount of flammable/corrosive material that had dripped from the botom of the drum onto the truck and ground was cleaned up with an absorbant pad. The absorbant pad was also placed into the 85 gallon overpack for shipment to the disposal site.
column169: Veolia employees are trained on an annual basis on how to handle these types of incidents. They responded to the incident as trained and handled the minor leak very well. The cause of the leak was undetermined as the drum appeared to be in very good shape except for a samll drip of material from the bottom chime. Veolia employees are trained to inspect every container before handeling and loading onto their vehicles.

column168: At approximately 17:00 hours on September 8, 2014, the Kansas City Southern (KCS) Critical Incident Desk was notified that the loaded crude oil tank car, ACFX 200134, was leaking clear liquid from the bottom outlet valve (BOV) in the Shreveport Yard. All concerned were notified. KCS dispatched a hazmat responder. Upon arrival the responder positioned containment under the BOV, and then determined that the top operated BOV was open.  The responder turned the valve four turns and then applied a 24" pipe wrench to close the valve tool tight.  The responder found the 6" cap loose and inside a defective gasket  The gasket was replaced, then the cap returned and tightened tool tight.    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: At approximately 10:40 hours on September 9, 2014, the Kansas City Southern (KCS) Critical Incident Desk was notified that the loaded crude oil tank car, CLIX 499148, was leaking from the manway in the Laredo Yard. All concerned were notified. KCS dispatched a hazmat responder. Upon arrival the responder determined that the all eight manway bolts were not tool tight (finger tight only) and that the manway gasket was missing. The responder installed a new gasket on the dome, closed the manway, and tightened the manway bolts tool tight.  The responder then wiped down the sides of the tank car with pads.    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: Tank car SRIX 33815 was reported emanating commodity odor while in the railyard. SRIX 33815 was cordoned-off in the railyard and yard operations were subsequently suspended. Contract responders inspecting SRIX 33815 determined the commodity odor/vapor was emanating from the top style Midland 280.5 psi pressure relief valve's (PRV) bolted connection to the tank cars pressure plate and from the PRV's top cap area.  An emergency response kit (Midland Capping Kit) was applied over the PRV to seal off escaping commodity vapor/odor by 0700 CDT, 9/08/2014. Afterwards, SRIX 33815 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting commodity transfer.  On 9/16/2014, contract responders transferred commodity within SRIX 33815 to another suitable tank car which was accomplished without incident by 1630 hrs. CDT, 9/16/2014. Air monitoring was initiated before and throughout the transfer process with no detectable levels of ammonia recorded. Afterwards, responders removed the applied Midland Capping mechanism and tool tightened the PRV flange bolt nuts (approximately two turns each). In addition, the PRV's O-rings were removed and replaced. The removed O-rings appeared to have signs of chemical degradation and flattening (compression set). The removed O-rings were sent to Carolina Seal for root cause failure analysis. After the PRV was secure, no commodity odor or vapor release was detectable. Responders re-inspected SRIX 33815 in the morning of 9/17/2014 and no commodity vapor leakage or odor was detected.

column168: During the loading process at the origin terminal, the drums were loaded onto a pallet and were being moved with a forklift. It was then placed into an overpack for later disposal. Due to the hazard of material, the package specifications were not able to be obtained.

column25: Changshu Hangmei Chemical Industry Co., Ltd
column168: On September 10, 2014 at 2330 EST, Tennessee Commercial Warehouse experienced the release of UN3265 from a 275 gallon plastic tote as result of a forklift puncture. The tote released its entire contents to the trailer floor, dock floor, and pavement beneath the trailer. Upon discovery, Tennessee Commercial Warehouse personnel retained Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS)to dispatch an Environmental Cleanup crew to assist with recovering the release. Once onsite, the crew installed absorbent pads underneath the damaged tote to collect leaking residual product. The impacted areas were neutralized, and the product was solidified using granular absorbents. All spent absorbents were containerized in a roll-off box for proper disposal.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On Wednesday September 24, 2014 at ~7:00 am a tanker truck loaded with Acetaldehyde arrived at Pfizer Kalamazoo MI to be unloaded. When the operators were pressurizing the tanker to prepare for the transfer they noticed a leak from the tanker relief valve. This was at ~ 9:00 am. We were not sure if the release occurred from the valve or from a gasket on the pressure relief device.  Unloading could not occur with the leaking pressure relief device. It was determined the best course of action was to move the tanker away from the storage tanks to a remote location on Pfizer property. That movement occurred at ~ 12:00 pm.  That required traffic to be stopped for less than 1 hour near the site to allow safe movement of the tanker to the remote location. The supplier was contacted and brought a new valve from Chicago, but they contract Valley City to swap the valves out. The supplier did not do the work themselves. The repair was completed ~5:30 pm that same day. The truck was inspected after the valve change out, and a 7 psi nitrogen pad was added to the tanker before leaving the site at ~ 8:00 pm.
column169: The Supplier and Transport Company will need to address the maintenence on the tanker trucks before they deliver product to the customer to ensure there is no malfunction of their equipment.

column168: A BNSF train stopped on the main track was reported with entrained tank car CBTX 740325 leaking commodity from its top fitting area. BNSF responders were able to stop the commodity release from CBTX 740325's liquid valve. Absorbent pads were placed at the valve housing area and CBTX 740325 was set-out of its train at the next/nearby rail terminal (Dilworth, MN). Contract responders cleaned the ground spillage where CBTX 740325 was initially found leaking commodity and cleaned the spillage from CBTX 740325 at the Dilworth terminal. Inspection revealed that liquid had by-passed the closed liquid valve and the TODO 4 inch high flow self-sealing coupling system applied onto the liquid valve.  CBTX 740325 isolated in the railyard is awaiting a replacement liquid valve that has been ordered and after this new valve is installed a contractor is scheduled to perform a leakage pressure test.

column168: A vehicle operated by Safety Kleen Systems, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation, it was discovered two drums had been double stacked and leaning to one side.  The compromised drum had begun to leak and when removing the 2-drum pallet, the leaning drum fell causing the top to rupture resulting in material escaping from the drum to the van trailer floor and subsequently to an area of containment below the van trailer.   Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised  container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and  placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: Management Team Investigation was conducted and the conclusion is this was a driver error.  Along with a  write-up to the driver, retraining is required with clear instruction that when drums of liquid are double stacked on trailer, the base must be wide and strong enough to support the material and the material must be secure from movement in all directions; and straps or load locks are to be used so as to ensure no movement.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: After arrival in the railyard on an inbound BNSF train, entrained tank car PROX 31757 was reported leaking commodity from its top fitting area with ice/frost forming around the exterior of its protective valve housing area. The local Klamath-Lake Hazmat Response Team responded and reported finding both liquid valves and the vapor valve within the valve housing area not secured with liquid commodity emanating from one of the liquid valves. All valves were reported to be 1/2 to 3/4 turns from full closure. One liquid valve with a loose closure plug was leaking liquid commodity from the plug's orifice. The vapor valve with a loose closure plug was leaking vapors from the plug's orifice as well. The Hazmat Response Team closed all the valves and tightened the loose closure plugs which ended any further release of commodity. All spillage evaporated.  Response was concluded by 1430 hrs. PDT, 9/09/2014. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders re-inspected PROX 31757 after its arrival in Barstow, CA and all valves and fittings were found secure.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: Tank car GATX 17859 in the railyard was reported with a fresh commodity stain on its side shell that emanated from its top valve housing area. Contract responders inspecting GATX 17859 reported its liquid valve was partially open by 1/8 turn with this valve's closure plug not tool tight. This allowed commodity to seep out from this unsecured valve port. Responders closed the liquid valve and tool tightened its closure plug which ended the commodity release. All other valves and fittings were found secure. Intact shipper seal numbered 410147 at the valve housing cover was replaced by seal numbered 410119. All spillage evaporated. Response was concluded prior to 1730 hrs. CDT, 9/11/2014.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: The shipment was properly offered as an overpack on the outermost box. As there are no closure instructions for an overpack and based on my expeience where in many shippers make hidden errors on inner packages of overpacks, I instructed Boise FedEx DG personnel to open & inspect the contents. Upon opening the overpack box we observed a UN POP 4G box that was missing the ATA 300 Cat I and DOT 31FP markings.I immediately mandated that the freight be held pending an FAA inspection. I notified the FAA, I spoke to HazMat Manager Drew Strabala with the Denver SECFO.

column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING PRODUCT (GASOLINE) INTO BULK TANK 1. HIS ASSUMPTION WAS THAT THE TANK WAS EMPTY. TANK GUAGE WAS FUNCTIONING. HE HEARD PRODUCT STARTING TO VENT SO HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN PTO. PRODUCT WAS RELEASED OUT OF THE TOP VENT. PRODUCT RAN DOWN TANK INTO SECONDARY CONTAINMENT.
column169: TANK MONITOR GAUGE WAS FOUND TO BE BROKEN. GAUGE WAS REPAIRED IMMEDIATELY BY MAINTENANCE STAFF. OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED FOR REMOVAL OF PRODUCT OUT OF THE CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN UP. REMINDED TO ALL DRIVERS TO CHECK GAUGE AND ALARMS BEFORE AND DURING OFFLOADING.

column168: CAUSE OF FAILURE - UNKNOWN; THIS SHIPMENT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING DURING THE SORT. STANDARD SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS WERE TWO PRODUCTS, ONE WAS THE UN 1760, CORROSIVE LIQUID, N.O.S., 8, AND THE 2ND WAS UN 3109, ORGANIC PEROXIDE TYPE F LIQUID, 5.2 PG II. CLASS 9 AND DIVISION 5.2 ARE INCOMPATIBLE PER THE 49CFR SEGREGATION TABLE SO THE SHIPPER SHOULD HAVE USED SEPARATE PACKAGES. I INSTRUCTED THE DG SPILL SPECIALIST TO SEPARATE EACH PRODUCT INTO SEPARATE DRUMS FOR THIS REASON PRIOR TO THE FAA'S ARRIVAL. AS THE SHIPPER HAD NOT OFFERED THE SHIPMENT WITH ANY DG MARKINGS, DG LABELS, A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION NOR WAS THERE AN AIRBILL/AUTOMATION LEVEL ENTRY THAT DG WAS PRESENT, ITS BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED OR HIDDEN DG. THE SAFETY DATA SHEETS FOR EACH PRODUCT WERE OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER WHICH CONFIRMED THEY ARE DG PRODUCTS.

I INSTRUCTED THE DG SPILL SPECIALIST TO SEPARATE EACH PRODUCT INTO SEPARATE DRUMS FOR THIS REASON PRIOR TO THE FAA'S ARRIVAL. AS THE SHIPPER HAD NOT OFFERED THE SHIPMENT WITH ANY DG MARKINGS, DG LABELS, A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION NOR WAS THERE AN AIRBILL/AUTOMATION LEVEL ENTRY THAT DG WAS PRESENT, ITS BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED OR HIDDEN DG. THE SAFETY DATA SHEETS FOR EACH PRODUCT WERE OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER WHICH CONFIRMED THEY ARE DG PRODUCTS.

column62: Missing Component or Device; Valve Open
column168: Entrained tank car UTLX 23432 was reported leaking commodity from its top fitting area while in the railyard after its arrival on an inbound BNSF train. UTLX 23432 was cordoned-off. Local F.D. responders arrived and closed the liquid valve that was partially open (1/4 turn) which ended the commodity release.  Also the closure plugs for the liquid valve and the vapor valve were not applied and laying atop the valve housing plate.  Afterwards contract responders applied Teflon tape to the threads of both closure plugs and installed the plugs to a tool tight condition into their respective valve ports. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. The product outage was checked and deemed sufficient. Intact shipper seals NCP 018741 at the manway and NCP 018740 applied at the protective housing cover were replaced by seals TIS 5133 and TIS 5134 respectively. Absorbent pads were applied over non-evaporated spillage.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Entrained covered hopper SIRX 525313 was reported leaking commodity from one of its four bottom outlets. The BNSF train was stopped on the BNSF main track to remedy and remediate this commodity release. BNSF mechanical responders reported SIRX 525313's A-end bottom outlet was slightly open (approximately 1 1/2 inches) due to the failure of this outlet's locking mechanism.  Responders closed this bottom outlet and secured it with cables to prevent re-opening.  A contractor vacuumed observed spillage and placed the captured spillage into disposal drums for appropriate future landfill disposal. Response was concluded by 1900 hrs. CDT, 9/19/2014.

column168: A 55-gallon steel drum of NA1993 Combustible liquids experienced a puncture during loading operations. The carrier, R&L Carriers, attempted a patch job that was unsuccessful, causing the drum to leak during transit. Approximately 3-4 gallons released from the drum onto the trailer floor and dirt parking lot at a gas station in Ida, LA on September 23, 2014. No drains or waterways were impacted. USES responded out of Shreveport, LA to clean the release and overpack the damaged drum. The drum was overpacked into (1) 85-gallon steel overpack and the released material was cleaned with granular absorbent and containerized thereafter. All contaminated materials were taken for disposal by USES. The site was restored to its previous condition.
Driver overfilled the tank causing 4 gallons to spill from the top of the tank. Service responded and properly cleaned, contained and disposed of the spill.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: MDOT Inspector Tommy Thomas noted product coming from the pressure relief device of tank car TEIX 25105 (L / Combustible Liquids, N.O.S. NA1993) during a roll by train inspection at the CN Jackson Yard, Jackson, MS. All appropriate departments notified and tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting oil in the SRV housing and running down the sides of the railcar. The railcar pressure was checked, and was observed by pressure gauge to have a vacuum. The outage on the railcar was checked using the magnetic ball gauging device and was determined to be not overloaded.  Its was determined that there could possibly be a faulty PRD. The exterior of the railcar was cleaned of all product residue. The shipper has applied for an OTMA.

column168: CN Transportation Department employee reported a liquid coming down the side of tank car UTLX 500136 (L/ Flammable Liquids, N.O.S. UN 1993) during switching operations at the CN Geismar Yard, Geismar, LA. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN response team responded noting liquid dripping from the combination housing.  The combination housing was found secured by shipper's seal.  The seal was cut and combination housing lid was opened.  The vapor valve was observed in the open position and the plug was not installed.  The vapor valve was closed and the plug was installed tool tight.  The tank car was released for movement.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: Entrained tank car PROX 44085 was reported emanating a commodity odor prior to its train departure from the railyard. BNSF and contract responders inspecting PROX 44085 reported finding the applied manway nozzle gasket deteriorated and partially torn; thusly not providing a good seal. A new manway nozzle gasket was installed and the manway cover was re-secured which ended the commodity odor/vapor release. No liquid commodity release was observed, but a very small dried residue stain near the manway nozzle was wiped.  All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. Intact shipper seals removed were replaced by Wenck seal 2586 at the manway closure and Wenck seal 2585 at the protective housing cover. Response was concluded by 2115 hrs. CDT, 9/19/2014.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

The valve was closed, shipping plug inserted, and packing nut secured. Tank car had security seals installed and the car was released to transportation for further movement.

column168: On September 26, 2014, a LLL Transport Model 507 tanker trailer was involved in a single vehicle accident that resulted in the tanker being punctured from the tool-box after the driver hit a large curb. Approximately 100-150 gallons of UN1987 Ethanol Alcohols 97%, NOS released onto a gravel area measuring approximately 125'x20'. B&P responded out of North Little Rock, AR to remediate the release and minimize damage to the Sit-go property. A transfer of the material from the compromised tanker was conducted. All material was transferred into a 40,000 gallon frac tank and staged on-site temporarily pending disposal/reclamation. On September 30, 2014, excavation of the impacted area was completed per AZ DEQ request. All contaminated soils were taken for disposal. The site was restored to its previous condition.

column62: Overfilled; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: THE DROP FITTING THAT MUST BE USED AT THIS SITE HAS THE VAPOR VENTING UP AROUND THE DROP TUBE, THEN CONNECTS TO THE TANKER BY A VAPOR HOSE. THE HOSE HAS LOCKING EARS TO PREVENT DISCONNECTION. AS THE TANK FILLED TO THE 90% LEVEL, WITH NO ALARM, THE FUEL FLOWED UP THE VAPOR RETURN. THE VIBRATION ALLOWED THE EARS TO LOOSEN, SPILLING GRAVITY FED DIESEL. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE BELLY VALVE ON THE TANKER AND STARTED TO CONTAIN SPILL. HE USED PADS AND OIL DRY TO STOP THE FLOW THE UNDER 30 GALLON SPILL. TAS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALL TO CLEAN SITE AND REMOVE WASTE PRODUCTS RETAIN OF ONLY 134 GALLONS WAS SENT TO VALERO STORE #1071.
column169: SUGGESTION TO PREVENT REACCURANCE WOULD BE TO UPDATE VAPOR DROP TUBE TO NOW ALLOW VAPOR AND FUEL IN THE SAME FITTING. THE 90% ALARMS SHOULD BE A WARNING TO HELP PREVENT OVERFILLS, BUT ARE USELESS IF NO ONE CAN HEAR THEM, THERE SHOULD BE ALARMS UNDER CANOPY FOR DRIVER TO HEAR. QUICK DISCONNECTS SHOULD ALL HAVE LOCKING EARS WITH CHAIN BACKUP LATCHES. THE FIRST LINE OF PROTECTION WOULD BE FOR THE DRIVER TO STICK THE TANKS BEFORE DROPPING EVERY TIME AND THEN RECEIVE AN ATG COPY TO VERIFY AVAILABLE SPACE, BEFORE ONE DROP GOES INTO TANKS.

column168: During loading operation driver re-entered cab of truck in violation of policy and proper procedures and fell asleep. Driver failed to hear overfill alarm when it sounded. These human failure resulted in the overfill and spillage of 65 barrels of crude oil. Measures were immediately implemented to contain the spill and clean up crews and equipment were immediately dispatched to the scene. Air monitoring was put into place while crews used the best equipment and materials available to mitigate the effects of the spill. NRC notification was made and clean up was under the direct supervison of six Federal and State agencies.
column169: Driver was terminated for failure to follow standard procedures and critical practices. A training presentation was prepared for use at future safety meetings and employees were reminded of the importance that all loading and unloading procedures be followed to the letter.

column168: Cryogenic tank car IAPX 1050 standing in a yard track in the railyard was reported with frost covering the bottom of its side operating/equipment cabinet.  A nearby consignee responder thawed the icing within the equipment cabinet to determine the commodity leak source. Once thawing was completed, the valve labeled 'LL Liquid Phase' (LL= Liquid Line) was closed ending any further release of commodity. This valve is normally open during transportation.  It appeared that a defective or loose coupling fitting on the 1/4 inch diameter stainless steel line connection from this valve into a 'Data Port' monitoring device with remote monitoring capability inside the equipment cabinet was the source of the leak.

column168: On September 22, 2014 at 0600 EST, R&L Carriers personnel discovered a leaking 55-gallon drum of UN1224 Ketones upon opening a trailer door during the unloading process. Approximately 2 cups of material had released to the rim/body of the drum and trailer floor due to a faulty rolled edge seam on the bottom of the drum.  Upon discover, R&L Carriers retained Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS)to dispatch an environmental response company to assist with cleanup. ERTS dispatched Wenck Response Services, Inc. who placed the leaking drum into an 85-gallon overpack drum and utilized an explosion proof fan to assist with evaporation/vaporization of the released material until vapor levels were 10 percent of the LEL.

The Employee reported that after he made a right hand turne from a stop sign the hose became disconnected from the truck.  100 feet of hose unleashed and then connected to the stop sign. column168: Driver had been unloading by use of his truck mounted pump for about 30 minutes when a pin hole developed in his 2 in camlock delivery hose. He immediately shut the pump down. He removed the damaged hose with another hose and resumed pumping.

Driver was unloading. When he opened the cargo tank trailer valves product leaked out of one of the cam lock fittings. Driver discovered the hose did not have a gasket. He installed a gasket in the female end of the hose and proceded with unloading.     Driver failed to check the hose prior to connection to ensure a gasket was in place.

column168: On 9/28/2014, at 09:25, personnel in the CSXT Rice Yard discovered GATX 18375, a loaded tank car of sulfuric acid, leaking from the pressure relief device. The car was isolated and the shipper Southern States Chemical, the State of Georgia, and the NRC were notified.  CHEMTREC Report # 2014092800015.  First Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the rupture disk actuated. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper John Fogarty 912-288-4353. Contractor personnel replaced the rupture disk and decontaminated the car and cleaned up the spilled material. GATX replaced the Salco PRD, bubble leak tested it and re-qualified the tank car.  This incident did not require a special switching move.  A 7.1 is not required.     Cause Code:  NARRI: 1004

column168: On September 24th 2014, the carrier (Seaboard Marine) was advised by the Freight Forwarder (AMCAR FOWARDING INC) that undeclared hazardous materials were stowed inside container SMLU831037-6 (UN1133 ADHESIVES). The container was on terminal grounds at the time we (Seaboard Marine) received notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded.  Upon receiving notice from the shipper we immediately placed a HOLD on the container and prohibited future movement. The shipper was asked to provide the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. The same day, upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and subsequently released for transportation

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While unloading, one (1) 55-gallon drum was punctured by a forklift. Approximately 35 gallons of free product were released. Free product released to the asphalt surface, and was contained. There was no impact to surface soils or threat to enter state waters. Wilson Trucking Corporation utilized their spill kit, and applied absorbent material to the affected area. Spent absorbents were recovered and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon recovery drum, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations. The damaged drum was overpacked, and placed in the terminal OS&D, pending disposition. There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Wilson Trucking Corporation will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: On September 29, 2014 at 0848 EST Dupre Logistics contacted ERTS in regards to a release of gasoline from a 406 tanker (Manifest# 1560077). Less than 5 gallons released onto the asphalt. The fire dept. was the first to arrive on-scene and secured/contained the release. The cause of the release was reported to be driver error during unloading. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release. ERTS dispatched a contractor to the site for initial response and remediation activities.

Intermodal container SEGU469694 was discovered to be leaking product. Upon further investigation, the source of the release was found to be a 330 gallon IBC.  The cause of release was load shift due to lack of lateral bracing allowing the tote to move and continuously flex and stress the plastic receptacle and cage, creating a tear. All necessary clean up was performed and completed. Container secured and released to its intended destination.

column168: As the operator was completing the unload of the rail car, he noticed that there was a small leak of 65% nitric acid around the unloading flange. He also noticed that there was a small leak of 65% nitric acid leaking onto the ground.The weld on the drain pipe that runs from the top of the rail car to the belly had a small pin-hole leak in it. The safety and environmental departments were immediately notified. The acid that leaked onto the ground was neutralized with soda ash. The car was immediately tagged out of service. On further inspection the car was noted to have two loose bolts that were less than finger tight that fasten top liquid valve to top valve plate. The leak in the drain line causedthe Nitric Acid to leak on the ballast.
column169: We are looking at improving our unloading procedure to include a more thorough inspection of rail cars before they are unloaded.

column168: SUBCONTRACTOR DRIVER, KENNETH FREEMAN, USED A FORKLIFT TO UNLOAD A 55 GALLON DRUM AT OUR SHERMAN, TX FACILITY. DURING THIS PROCESS HE TORE A HOLE IN THE SIDE OF THE DRUM RELEASING CONTENTS OF THE DRUM ONTO OUR CEMENT DOCK AREA. HE THEN CLOSED EVERYTHING UP AND CONTINUED ON HIS WAY BACK TO OUR DALLAS, TX FACILITY. AFTER LEAVING THE SHERMAN TERMINAL, KENNETH CALLED THE NIGHT SUPERVISOR IN MCCALESTER, OK-MR. BULLARD, WHO IN TURN CALLED THE SAFETY DIRECTOR, MR. MYERS. MR. MYERS CONTACTED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT AND STARTED THE PROCESS OF CONTAINMENT AND CLEANUP. MR. HOOPER, WITH ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT CONTACTED KENNETH AND INQUIRED ABOUT THE RELEASE. THE DRIVER STATED THAT THE TRAILER MIGHT OR MIGHT NOT HAVE BEEN IMPACTED. MR. HOOPER INFORMED THE DRIVER, UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DALLAS TERMINAL, TO PARK THE TRUCK IN A REMOTE AREA, LEAVING THE DOORS OPEN FOR VENTILATION, VACATE THE AREA AND HAVE THE TERMINAL MANAGER CONTACT HIM. UPON ARRIVAL OF TAS PERONNEL, IT WAS OBSERVED THAT THE MAJORITY OF THE RELEASED PRODUCT HAS DISSIPATED DUE TO EVAPORATION. TAS PERSONNEL IDENTIFIED THE RELEASE PRODUCT AS A CLEANING AGENT CONTAINING DICHLOROMETHANE AND TETRACHLOROETHYLENE. THE OVER-TURNED DRUM CONTAINED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RESIDUAL INSIDE. THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN A 95-GALLON POLY OVER PACK FOR TRANSPORT. TAS RESPONSE PERSONNEL THEN UTILIZED ABSORBENTS TO RECOVER THE REMAINING FREE PRODUCT, PLACING THE IMPACTED ABSORBENTS IN THE OVER PACK FOR DISPOSAL. ONCE THE FREE PRODUCT WAS REMOVED, TAS UTILIZED A SOLUTION OF SIMPLE GREEN TO THOROUGHLY MOP THE AREA, REMOVING ANY REMAINING RESIDUALS OF THE PRODUCT, PLACING THE RESIDUALS IN THE OVER PACK FOR DISPOSAL.  THE MOPPED AREA WAS THEN ALLOWED TO AIR-DRY COMPLETELY. TAS RESPONSE PERSONNEL NOTICED A SMALL AREA OF GRASS WHICH WAS POSSIBLY IMPACTED FROM THE PRODUCT BY RUNOFF. MR HOOPER INSTRUCTED RESPONSE PERSONNEL TO HAND-EXCAVATE THE AREA, DUE TO THE POSSIBLE SOIL CONTAMINATION. AN AREA OF 1 FOOT X 1 FOOT WAS EXCAVATED AND PLACED IN A 55-GALLON DRUM FOR DISPOSAL. A SAMPLE WAS ALSO TAKEN TO BE ANALYZED FOR THE PRESENCE OF THE CHEMICALS OF CONCERN. THE TRAILER WAS ALSO INSPECTED AND NO SIGN OF RESIDUALS, AND NO INDICATION OF CHEMICAL ODOR WAS FOUND. MR. MYERS SENT MR. HOOPER A COPY OF THE BILL-OF-LADING AND MSDS SHEETS FOR THE PRODUCT. UPON RECEIPT MR. HOOPER CONTACTED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (NRC) AT APPROXIMATELY 1330 CST (REF#1096934), AND THE TEXAS COMMISSION FOR ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY (REPORT #20143376) AT APPROX 1420CST.
column169: Suggested Additional training to the subcontractor and his drivers.

column169: 9/26/2014: At approximately 8:45PM, Trainmaster Higgins advised CR crew FC05 had reported an undefined odor in Pavonia Yard, Camden, NJ, in close proximity to a string of tank cars on #11 Support in the yard that had arrived earlier in the day off of CR FP63-26.  Another crew confirmed the same odor.    CR emergency response contractor Hepaco contacted to inspect and ascertain the origination of the odor.      9/27/2014:  At 01:38AM, received call from Hepaco's R. Gould, advising odor was found to be originating from tank car UTLX 92617, containing the residue of Vinyl Chloride.  Slight vapor odor detected by meter, measuring approximately 14 ppm.  Root cause noted to be both (2) liquid valves not closed and closure plugs not tool tight; and the vapor valve was also partially open and same closure plug not tool tight.  Car secured during inspection.

column168: SJ trailer V1026 was in held in temporary storage at our facility in Woodstown, NJ pending delivery to its final destination.  During a normal yard check of the trailer, the trailer floor appeared wet and the top of several totes appeared wet.  SJ called the account manager at Veolia Environmental Services, who then received approval from Global Foundries to contact an ER response team.  Lewis Environmental responded to SJ to investigate the liquid.  Lewis determined there were several caps that were not properly secured.  Lewis cleaned the trailer floor and the totes.  They then correctly sealed the caps on the totes.  The material was then delivered to Pencco Inc. in Middlesex, NC. The release was all contained within the trailer and estimated to be approximately 1 gallon.
column169: SJ operations personnel discussed with Veolia that all caps need to be properly secured per UN specifications.

SCHROEDER ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIORNMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: KA BULK TRANSPORT, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE LOADING/UNLOADING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

column168: WHILE LOADING, A DRUM OF PRODUCT WAS DAMAGED. THE DRUM AND AFFECTED MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND LINED SALVAGE DRUMS. THE DRUMS ARE BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION.
column169: MAKE SURE EQUIPMENT IS WORKING PROPERLY.

column168: DRIVER SHANE ASHWORTH EMPLOYEE OF L.M. DAIGLE OIL DISTRIBUTOR, LLC SPILLED 30 GALLONS OF ULTRA LO SULFUR DIESEL #2 ON CUSTOMER SITE AT SUPERIOR CARRIERS 2023 TANKER DRIVER SULPHUR, LA.70663; THE DRIVER THEN ENGAGED PTO PUMP AND STARTED PUMPING FUEL TO TANK WHILE NOT BEING IN CLEAR VIEW OF THE HOSE TO CUSTOMER TANK.  ONCE DRIVER TURNED TOWARD DISCHARGE HOSE; HE REALIZED FUEL WAS LEAKING FROM CAMLOCK FITTING AND IMMEDIATELY STOPPED PUMPING. THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS DUE TO A 3" GASGET MISSING FROM CAMLOCK FITTING THAT THE DRIVER USED TO ATTACHED TO THE CUSTOMER TANK FILL CONNECTOR VALVE ON THE TANK. THE DRIVER THEN IMMEDIATELY GRABBED THE SPILL KIT ON THE TRUCK AND PLACED SORBENT PADS ON GROUND TO CONTAIN SPILL.  DRIVER THEN NOTIFIED KEVIN DAIGLE, THE SAFETY SUPERVISOR, AND HE RESPONDED TO THE SITE TO EVALUATE THE SPILL. AFTER ARRIVING TO THE SITE KEVIN DAIGLE CALLED ES&H ENVIORNMENTAL TO RESPOND TO CLEAN UP THE CONTAMINATED LIMESTONE ROCK. STATE POLICE HOTLINE WAS NOTIFIED AT 3:35 PM TO REPORT SPILL (SPILL REPORT# 14-03986 SPOKE TO TARA GUIDRY). THE SPILL AREA MEASURED 8X8 ON LIMESTONE ROCK BY TANK.
column169: DRIVER SHANE ASHWORTH WAS INSTRUCTED OF L.M. DAIGLE OIL DISTRIBUTOR LLC POLICIES OF DELIVERING PRODUCTS TO CUSTOMER IN SAFE MANNER AND TO INSURE THAT ALL FUTURE SPILL PREVENTION ACTION IS TO BE TAKEN AT ALL TIMES. THE DRIVER SIGNED AN ACKNOWLEDGEMENT OF A REPRIMAND LETTER. WE HAVE TAKEN STEPS TO PREVENT THE REOCCURENCE OF SPILLS.  THIS WAS REVIEWED AT A COMPANY SAFETY MEETING PERTAINING TO LOADING AND UNLOADING TRUCKS AT JOBSITES TO PREVENT FURTHER INCIDENTS.

column168: After unloading completed, driver closed valve on trailer and tail pump and unhooked product hose before ensuring any residual oil was removed. Oil leaked from end of hose while the driver moved it to the drip box.
column169: Additional training for employees on loading/unloading procedures.

column168: WHILE MOVING FREIGHT ON THE DOCK, ONE CARTON WAS PUNCTURED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. THE RELEASE WAS PROPERLY MANAGED. THE DAMAGED FREIGHT WAS PLACED INTO A LINED DRUM AND HELD PENDING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.
column169: USE CAUTION WORKING AROUND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ON THE DOCK.

column168: DRIVER CLAIMS WHILE TRAVELING ON HIGHWAY, A VEHICLE ENTERED THE HIGHWAY FROM THE SHOULDER AND HE APPLIED HARD BRAKING TO AVOID A REAR END COLLISION. DRIVER STATED HE FELT A TUG AND LOOKED IN HIS DRIVERS SIDE MIRROR NOTICED THE IBC ON THE GROUND.  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY EXITED THE HIGHWAY AND NOTIFIED CARRIER AND EMERGENCY FIRE PERSONNEL. GARY, IN FIRE PERONNEL ARRIVED WITHIN 5-6 MINUTES AND APPLIED ABSORBENTS ON THE ROAD SURFACE IN ADDITION TO PLACING DIRT AROUND STORM DRAIN. INDUSTRIAL & ENVIORNMENTAL SERVICES, LLC. WAS DISPATCHED BY CARRIER TO THE SPILL LOCATION WITHIN 30 MINUTES AND APPLIED ABSORBENTS AND POLY SHEETING. INDSUTRIAL & ENVIORNMENTAL SERVICES EXTRACTED CHEMICALS FROM THE LEAKING IBC TO ANOTHER AS THE DAMAGED IBC HAD SPLIT APPROXIMATELY 5" MIDWAY OF IBC.
column169: THE INCIDENT WAS REVIEWED WITH THE CONTRACT DRIVER AND DETERMINED HE FAILED TO HAVE ADEQUATE LOAD SECUREMENT DEVICES IN HIS POSSESSION AS REQUIRED. THE CONTRACT DRIVER HAS BEEN SCHEDULED FOR A REFRESHER COURSE ON PROPER LOAD SECUREMENT.

Call received 07:00 PST in Safety Department.  Roll-over hazardous materials incident Cabazon, CA occurred at 06:45 PST on I-10 WB at Haugan Lehman Road near Cabazon CA.  Driver looked down and then he looked up, he realized he was too close to the guard rail. Drove 40'-50' feet along guard rail to cement bridge, clipping bridge.  Driver tried to correct, but by this time the trailers started to tip. Driver over-corrected and the trailers flipped over on the right side. The set skidded several feet and started on fire. The tractor and the entire set were burned. Total cost still unknown at this time.  Riverside County Environmental Health Department (#Co 0051448), Cal Trans, CHPD and Riverside County Fire responded to initial scene and during clean-up remediation.  Fire Department used water and foam to extinguish fire.  Water, foam and other materials left the roadway and some entered a drain.  Emergency response contractor cleaned up all materials, excavated soil and mitigated release to drain. Soil back filled as needed.  Union Pacific and California Fish and Game were satisfied with cleanup activities as an estimated 240 yards of waste was generated across 12 roll offs.  Inner packaging types unknown.     HM cargo included: 6 cases containing 2x2.5 gallons each of UN3082, Environmentally hazardous substances, liquid, nos, (thiophante-methyl), 9, III 6 drums containing 48x1 lb drum each of UN3077, Environmentally hazardous substances, solid, nos (thiophanate-methyl), 9, IIII  Non-cargo and Non HM included Petroleum  diesel fuel  1  Gallons   Petroleum  motor oil  1  Gallons   Non-HazMat (Specify Description)  Dipel PRO DF  90  Pounds   Non-HazMat (Specify Description)  Safari 20 SG  192  Ounces   Non-HazMat (Specify Description)  Arena 50 WDG  160  Ounces   Non-HazMat (Specify Description)  Polaris  25  Gallons   Non-HazMat (Specify Description)  Overture 35 WP  128  Ounces   Non-HazMat (Specify Description)  Tetrasan 5 WDG  128  Ounces  Amount listed on page 1 of 5800.1 as far as capacity was entered to enable the creation of the form in IT system. column42: ENGINES INTERNAL COMBUSTION, OR ENGINES, FUEL CELL, FLAMMABLE LIQUID POWERED
column168: THE SUSPECTED ENGINE WAS TRUCKED FORM ELK GROVE VILLAGE, IL TO THE UPS CSI CARGO CENTER IN DALLAS TX, TO BE FORWARDED TO DESTINATION IN HOUSTON , TX. THE CARGO WAS SHIPPED "DL" OR DELAYED SERVICE, WHICH IS PRIMARILY GROUND SERVICE, BUT COULD GO AIR. ALTHOUGH UNLIKELY THIS CARGO WOULD HAVE TRAVELED VIA AIR FROM DALLAS TO HOUSTON, THIS IS BEING REPORTED AS AN "UNDECLARED" AS IT WAS SHIPPED USING A SERVICE THAT COULD HAVE POSSIBLY GONE AIR.  AROUND 04:30 ON 09/12/2014 UPS CSI HANDLERS IN DALLAS UNLOADING THE CARGO NOTICED THAT IT APPEARED TO BE AN ENGINE-POWERED DEVICE, THAT ALSO APPEARED TO HAVE PREVIOUSLY BEEN USED OR OPERATED. A CLOSER INSPECTION DETECTED THE PRESENCE OF WHAT APPEARED TO BE ABOUT 1/4 TANK OF A GASOLINE-TYPE FUEL.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS, AND NO HAZMAT SHIPPING PAPERS. NO BOL OR AIR WAYBILL WAS PROVIDED BY THE SHIPPER INDICATING "NOT RESTRICTED AS PER SP A70".  THE SHIPMENT WAS IMMEDIATELY MOVED TO OUR TEMPORARY HAZMAT HOLDING AREA, WHERE IT REMAINS AWAITING FURTHER INSTRUCTION.  THIS SHIPMENT HAS NOT BEEN ACCEPTED FOR AIR OR TRANSPORTED IN THE AIR BY UNITED PARCEL SERVICE CO.
column169: THE SHIPPER SHOULD BE BETTER AWARE OF SERVICE LEVELS THAT COULD INCLUDE AIR TRANSPORT, AND PREPARE THE SHIPMENT AND PROVIDE DOCUMENTATION AS REQUIRED, UNLESS USING A CONFIRMED "GROUND-ONLY" SERVICE.  FOR UPS CSI, THE PICK-UP DRIVER AND HANDLERS AT ORIGIN SHOULD HAVE NOTICED THE CARGO AND REQUESTED APPROPRIATE DOCUMENTATION. THIS WILL BE REVIEWED WITH ALL AFFECTED STAFF AT ORIGIN.

column168: JCI JONES CHEMICALS INC DRIVER WAS OFF-LOADING SODIUM HYDROXIDE (CAUSTIC) INTO THREE "TOTE" TANKS AT OUR CUSTOMER SITE; I.E., WEST BASIN CARSON. THE DRIVER OFF-LOADED INTO THE FIRST TWO TOTE TANKS WITHOUT INCIDENT. DRIVER FINISHED OFF-LOADING INTO THE DINAL TANK AND BEGAN THE BLOWDOWN PROCESS. FOLLOWING THE BLOWDOWN PROCESS, DRIVER CRACKED OPEN ONE OF THE EARS IN THE 2' CAMLOCK FITTING ON THE UNLOADING HOSE IN PREPARATION FOR DISCONNECTING THE HOSE FROM THE CUSTOMER'S UNLOADING POINT. AT THAT MOMENT, THE CAUSTIC UNDER PRESSURE IN THE HOSE WAS RELEASED SPRAYING DRIVER WITH CAUSTIC ON HIS RIGHT LEG. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIAMETLY +/- 5 GALLONS OF CAUSTIC WAS SPILLED INTO THE CUSTOMER'S CONTAINMENT AREA AND ANOTHER +/- 1 GALLON WAS SPILLED ONTO THE SURROUNDING BLACKTOP SURFACE. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY RINSED SKIN FOR 10-15 MINUTES UNDER THE SAFETY SHOWER AT THE CUSTOMER'S SITE.
column169: PROPER OFF-LOADING PROCEDURES MUST BE FOLLOWED. THIS INCLUDES ENSURING THAT ALL APPROPRIATE VALVES HAVE BEEN CLOSED DURING EACH STAGE OF THE UNLOADING AND BLOWDOWN PROCESS.    IN ADDITION, DRIVERS MUST BE CERTAIN THAT ALL MATERIAL IS DISCHARGED COMPLETELY FORM THE HOSE BY BOTH CHECKING THE WEIGHT OF THE HOSE AND LISTENING FOR THE FREE FLOW OF AIR THROUGH THE UNLOADING HOSE.    ONE OF THE EARS IN THE CAMLOCK FITTING OF THE HOSE IS TO BE VERY SLOWLY CRACKED OPENED TO ENABLE THE DRIVER TO CONFIRM THAT THE HOSE IS IN FACT FREE OF BOTH PRESSURE AND PRODUCT.    LASTLY, THE IMPORTANCE OF THIS WILL BE RE-EMPHASIZED WITH ALL DRIVERS.

column168: THE TRUCK AND PUP TANK TRAILER WERE ON HIGHWAY 62 WEST OF NW 82ND STREET. PUP TANK TRAILER WAS TRACKING TO THE RIGHT AND STRUCK THE CURB. THIS CAUSED THE TRAILER TO BECOME UNSTEADY ROCKING SIDE TO SIDE. DRIVER REALIZED WHAT WAS HAPPENING AND ATTEMPTED TO REGAIN CONTROL OF THE TRAILER BY SLOWING DOWN. THE TRAILER CONTINUED TO ROCK AND OVERTURNED TO THE LEFT SIDE STILL ATTACHED TO THE TRUCK. DRIVER WAS ABLE TO STOP BOTH VEHICLES. DRIVER FOUND THERE HAD BEEN APPROXIMATELY 900 LBS OF PRODUCT RELEASED FROM THE TANK HATCH AND A CRACK IN THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER. CLEANUP WAS CONDUCTED BY BUCKLEY POWDER CO. PERSONNEL ON THE SCENE. THE CLEANUP WAS APPROVED BY OKLAHOMA DOT AND DEQ.

column168: THE DELIVERY TRUCK WAS TRAVELING OVER A GRAVEL CMP ROAD. THE DRIVER WAS DRIVING OVER A HUMP IN THE ROAD. THE HUMP HAD A SECTION OF LEDGE PROTRUDING FORM THE CENTER. AS THE TRUCK WENT OVER THE HUMP, THE PUMP GUARD BENEATH THE TRUCK STRUCK THE LEDGE. THE FORCE OF THE IMPACT CAUSED SEVERAL BOLTS HOLDING THE GUARD TO THE TRUCK FRAME TO BREAK, CAUSING THE GUARD TO PIVOT UPWARD AND STRIKING THE FILTER HOUSING ON THE PUMP AND BREAKING IT. THIS ALLOWED FUEL OIL TO BEGIN SPILLING ONTO THE GROUND THROUGH A GAP IN THE FILTER HOUSING THAT WAS ROUGHLY 3" LONG. THE DURATION LASTED 1-1 1/2 MINUTES OVER A DISTANCE OF 1/2 MILE OF GRAVEL ROADWAY. THE EMERGENCY SHUT OFF WAS ACTIVATED WHEN THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED BY THE DRIVER.
column169: A WIDER PUMP GUARD WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THE GUARD FROM STRIKING THE FILTER HOUSING WHEN IT PIVOTED UPWARD.

column168: DURING A VERMONT DOT CHECK AT A WEIGH STATION ON I-91 SOUTH, A GREASE FITTING ON THE PRODUCT PUMP BLEW OFF AND EMPTIED THE PRODUCT OUT OF THE PUMP UNTIL THERE WAS VAPOR. FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZMAT TEAMS WERE CALLED. HIGHWAY WAS SHUT DOWN AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. THE TRUCK WAS THEN ESCORTED TO A TERMINAL IN CLAREMONT, NH FOR OFF LOADING BY A COMPRESSOR.

DRIVER PICKED UP A LOAD IN PROVIDENCE, RI AND TRANSPORTED IT OT SOUTH PORTLAND MAINE. DRIVER CONNECTED TO PIPELINE AT TERMINAL TO PUMP OFF LOAD. DRIVER STARTED DELIVERY, CHECKING FOR LEAKS, AND CONFIRMED THAT AIR WAS FLOWING INTO TANK VENT, CONFIRMING PRODUCT FLOW. ALL OF A SUDDEN, THERE WAS A LOUD BANG, AND THEN THE DISCHARGE VALVE HOUSING SPLIT AT THE SEAMS. DRIVER WAS AT A PRODUCT FLOW VALVE AND IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE FLOW VALVE AND THEN STOPPED  THE PUMP. IT IS OUR OPINION, BASED UPON INFORMATION FROM OUR OTHER DRIVERS THAT WERE PRESENT, THAT A VALVE MUST HAVE SLAMMED CLOSED IN THE PIPELINE, CAUSING A "HAMMER" WHICH OVER PRESSURED THE ENTIRE SYSTEM. BUT THE DISCHARGE VALVE BODY WAS THE WEAKEST LINE, CAUSING IT TO FAIL.
column169: THE VALVE BODY THAT FAILED IS CONSTRUCTED OF TWO HALVES, THAT ARE WELDED TOGETHER.  WE HAVE STOPPED PURCHASING THIS TYPE OF VALVE AND HAVE SWITHCHED TO HEAVIER MOLDED BODY FLOW VALVES.

column168: During the screening of awb 1274-8562, a plastic case containing distress signal flares were found. The shipment has been placed on hold and waiting for the FAA to inspect. Also found was a container of Lifesmoke MK3.

Lumber truck began to make a U-Turn and failed to yield right a way to Sunoco Logistics truck.  Sunoco Logistics truck struck the lumber truck and both units caught on fire instantly.  The fire and extreme temperatures melted the trailer and the petroleum crude oil burned.  The drivers of both units were caught in the vehicles and burned.  The passenger in the lumber truck was able to get out of truck but suffered severe burns.
column169: At this time, there was no preventative action that could have been taken to avoid this accident.  It is stressed to all drivers and training is provided to drive as defensively as possible at all times.

column168: MTL DRIVER WAS TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON HIGHWAY I-90 ENTERING WASHINGTON STATE.  THE DRIVER WAS STOPPED AT THE WEIGH STATION MILE MARKER 298 NEAR LIBERTY WASHINGTON AND WAS PLACED OUT OF SERVICE.  A COMPLAINT HAD BEEN FILED BY A MOTORIST IN IDAHO THAT HAD BEEN FOLLOWING OUR UNIT, CLAIMING THAT THEY COULD SMELL PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER AND CLAIMED IT MUST BE LEAKING.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE WEIGH STATION THE DRIVER SPRAYED THE UNIT DOWN WITH HIS SPRAY BOTTLE AND NO LEAK COULD BE FOUND.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT & HAZMAT TEAM WERE CONTACTED.  IT WAS DECIDED TO BLEED THE JUMPER HOSES ON THE TRAILER TO SEE IF THAT WOULD CAUSE THE SMELL TO GO AWAY, BUT IT DIDN'T. AFTER NUMEROUS INSPECTIONS AND CAPPING A FITTING ON THE COMPRESSOR THE DRIVER WAS RELEASED TO GO BACK ON THE ROAD.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: DRIVER STATED THAT HE WAS TRAVELING NORTH BOUND ON HIGHWAY 431 AND AS HE CRESTED A HILL HE SAW TRAFFIC WAS STOPPED. ON THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE DIVIDED HIGHWAY A SCHOOL BUS WAS STOPPED TO UNLOAD. DRIVER STATED THAT HE HAD NO TIME TO STOP SO HE ATTEMPTED TO TAKE THE DITCH TO AVOID CAUSING INJURIES TO OTHER DRIVERS. WITNESS STATED THAT CARS IN FRONT OF HER WERE STOPPED BECAUSE THE SCHOOL BUS AND SHE STOPPED WHEN SHE HEARD THE TRUCK WRECK TO HER SIDE. OFFICERS OPINION THE TRUCK WOULD NOT HAVE HAD TIME TO STOP DUE TO THE BLIND SPOT FROM THE CREST OF THE HILL AND TRAFFIC WHICH WAS STOPPED ON THE HIGHWAY.
